---
source: crates/djinn-agent/src/prompts.rs
assertion_line: 987
expression: section
---
- `task_show(id)` — Show details of a work item including recent activity and blockers.
- `task_list(issue_type?, label?, limit?, offset?, parent?, priority?, sort?, status?, text?)` — List tasks with optional filters and pagination.
- `task_activity_list(id, actor_role?, event_type?, limit?)` — Query a task's activity log with optional filters. Returns comments, status transitions, verification results, and other events. Use to inspect Lead guidance, reviewer feedback, or verification history.
- `memory_read(identifier)` — Read a note by permalink or title.
- `memory_search(query, folder?, limit?, task_id?, type?)` — Search notes in project memory.
- `memory_list(depth?, folder?, type?)` — List notes in project memory. Returns compact summaries without full content.
- `shell(command, timeout_ms?)` — Execute shell commands in the task worktree. Commands always run from the worktree root.
- `read(file_path, limit?, offset?)` — Read a file with line numbers and pagination. Rejects binary files.
- `lsp(file_path, operation, character?, depth?, kind?, line?, name_filter?, symbol?)` — Query the Language Server Protocol for code navigation. Operations: hover (type info at position), definition (go to definition), references (find all references), symbols (list document symbols with optional depth/kind/name filtering). Line and character are 1-based for non-symbol operations.
- `code_graph(operation, project, changed_ranges?, confidence?, direction?, edge_kind?, end_line?, file?, file_glob?, from?, from_glob?, group_by?, key?, kind_filter?, limit?, max_depth?, min_size?, mode?, module_glob?, query?, rules?, seed_entries?, seed_sinks?, sort_by?, start_line?, symbols?, to?, to_glob?, visibility?, window_days?)` — Query the SCIP-built repository dependency graph. Set `operation` to one of the enum values; most ops accept optional filters (kind_filter, group_by, limit, min_confidence). Call `operation=capabilities` for the full per-op param shapes + defaults. Quick guide: neighbors / ranked / impact / implementations / search / cycles / orphans / path / edges — basic graph queries (impact defaults: depth=2, min_confidence=0.85, behavioural edges only). symbols_at / diff_touches / detect_changes — line-range → touched symbols. describe / context — single-symbol detail (context = bucketed incoming/outgoing edges). status / metrics_at / snapshot — graph health + introspection. api_surface / dead_symbols / deprecated_callers — public surface health. boundary_check / blast_radius / touches_hot_path — change-impact analysis. hotspots / cochange / churn / coupling_hubs — git-coupling × PageRank centrality.
- `pr_review_context(changed_ranges, project, boundary_rules?, caps?, hotspots_window_days?, seed_entries?, seed_sinks?)` — Given a PR's changed line ranges (parsed from `git diff --unified=0 base..head`), assemble the base-graph signals that matter for review in one call: touched symbols with fan-in/out, blast radius, hotspot overlap, touched cycles, deprecated-caller hits, hot-path overlap, and architecture-boundary violations. Base-graph-only — does NOT build a head graph, detect newly-introduced cycles, or parse the diff text for removed-API detection. Every list is capped (defaults: touched_symbols=100, blast_radius=50, hotspot_overlap=20, touched_cycles=20, touched_boundary_violations=50, touched_deprecated=20, hot_path_overlap=20).
- `ci_job_log(job_id, step?)` — Fetch the full log for a GitHub Actions CI job. When CI fails, the activity log tells you the job_id. Call this tool to see the actual error output. Optionally filter to a specific failed step name. If the output is large, use output_view or output_grep to navigate it.
- `github_search(query, language?, path?, repo?)` — Search GitHub code across public repositories using the GitHub Code Search API. Returns compact, navigable matches with snippets, file paths, URLs, and metadata. Each result has a result_id for reference. Use github_fetch_file to inspect the full file of a promising result.
- `github_fetch_file(path, repo, end_line?, ref?, start_line?)` — Fetch the full contents of a file from a public GitHub repository. Use after github_search to inspect a promising result. Supports optional start_line/end_line for reading specific sections of large files.
- `output_view(tool_use_id, limit?, offset?)` — Paginated view of a truncated tool output. When a tool result was truncated, the full output is stashed and can be browsed here by tool_use_id.
- `output_grep(pattern, tool_use_id, context_lines?)` — Regex search within a truncated tool output. Returns matching lines with context from the full stashed output.
- `task_create(acceptance_criteria, epic_id, title, blocked_by?, description?, design?, issue_type?, labels?, owner?, parent_id?, priority?, status?)` — Create a new task under an epic. Agents should use this only when explicitly allowed by their role and task design.
- `task_update(id, acceptance_criteria?, blocked_by_add?, blocked_by_remove?, description?, design?, epic_id?, memory_refs_add?, memory_refs_remove?, owner?, priority?, status?, title?)` — Update task fields and manage blocker relationships. Use blocked_by_add/blocked_by_remove to enforce task sequencing — a task with unresolved blockers will not be dispatched.
- `task_blocked_list(id)` — List tasks that are blocked by the given task. Use before decomposing to check downstream dependents.
- `epic_show(id)` — Show details for an epic by UUID or short ID.
- `epic_update(id, description?, memory_refs_add?, memory_refs_remove?, status?, title?)` — Update epic fields (title/description) and accept memory ref delta args for planner workflows.
- `epic_tasks(id, limit?, offset?)` — List tasks for an epic with pagination.
- `epic_close(id)` — Close an epic. Use when all work is complete and no further waves are needed.
- `epic_create(title, color?, description?, emoji?, memory_refs?, owner?, status?)` — Create a new epic (top-level grouping entity). Use to open a new strategic thread of work — typically when an Architect health sweep or chat planning session identifies a gap that needs its own delivery container. Returns the created epic.
- `task_transition(action, id, reason?, replacement_task_ids?)` — Transition a task using a named workflow action.
- `task_comment_add(body, id)` — Add a comment or strategic observation to a task's activity log.
- `memory_build_context(limit?, min_confidence?, query?, task_id?)` — Build a curated memory context pack for a task or query by combining note retrieval and ranking. Use this before deep analysis to gather relevant project history and decisions.
- `memory_health()` — Returns aggregate health report: total notes, broken link count, orphan note count, duplicate cluster count, low-confidence note count, stale note count, stale notes by folder.
- `memory_extracted_audit()` — Audit existing extracted case/pattern/pitfall notes against ADR-054 taxonomy and required structure. Returns grouped cleanup backlogs for merge candidates, underspecified notes, demotion-to-working-spec candidates, and archive candidates, plus rerun guidance.
- `memory_broken_links(folder?)` — Lists all broken wikilinks with source context (permalink, title, raw text, target permalink).
- `memory_orphans(folder?)` — Lists notes with zero inbound links. Excludes catalogs and singletons (brief, roadmap).
- `agent_metrics(role)` — Show execution quality metrics for a role to support prompt tuning and intervention decisions.
- `agent_create(base_role, name, description?, model_preference?, system_prompt_extensions?)` — Create a new specialist agent extending a base role (worker or reviewer). Use when existing agents lack capabilities for a specific domain.
- `memory_write(content, title, type, status?, tags?)` — Compatibility fallback for note creation when filesystem writes are unavailable. Prefer filesystem note CRUD via the mounted memory tree or checked-in `.djinn/` files. When mounted, `.djinn/memory/` reflects the current session-selected task/worktree view and falls back to canonical `main` when no task view is available; no explicit branch directories are exposed in this slice. Type is required and determines storage folder (adr->decisions/, pattern->patterns/, case->cases/, pitfall->pitfalls/, research->research/, requirement->requirements/, reference->reference/, design->design/, tech_spike->research/technical, session->research/sessions). Singleton types (brief, roadmap) write a fixed file — one per project. Use [[wikilinks]] in content to connect notes.
- `memory_edit(content, identifier, operation, find_text?, section?, type?)` — Compatibility fallback for note edits when filesystem writes are unavailable. Prefer filesystem note CRUD via the mounted memory tree or checked-in `.djinn/` files. When mounted, `.djinn/memory/` reflects the current session-selected task/worktree view and falls back to canonical `main` when no task view is available; no explicit branch directories are exposed in this slice. Operations: "append" (add to end), "prepend" (add after frontmatter), "find_replace" (exact text replacement, requires find_text), "replace_section" (replace content under a markdown heading, requires section).
- `memory_move(identifier, type, title?)` — Compatibility fallback for note moves when filesystem rename semantics are unavailable. Prefer filesystem note CRUD via the mounted memory tree or checked-in `.djinn/` files. When mounted, `.djinn/memory/` reflects the current session-selected task/worktree view and falls back to canonical `main` when no task view is available; no explicit branch directories are exposed in this slice. Updates permalink and resolves inbound links. Use type="proposed_adr" to recover a mis-routed ADR draft into .djinn/decisions/proposed/ without raw shell relocation.
- `task_delete_branch(id)` — Delete the task's git branch, worktree, and paused session so the next worker starts with a clean slate.
- `task_archive_activity(id)` — Soft-delete all activity entries (comments, session errors, rejections) for a task. The worker on the next attempt will only see post-intervention activity.
- `task_reset_counters(id)` — Reset reopen_count and continuation_count to zero. Use when the task has been meaningfully rescoped and old retry history is no longer relevant.
- `task_kill_session(id)` — Kill the paused worker session and delete its saved conversation. The next dispatch will start a fresh session. Unlike task_delete_branch, this preserves the branch and any committed code.
- `submit_work(commit_title, summary, task_id, files_changed?, remaining_concerns?)` — Signal that the worker has finished implementing the task. Provide a summary of changes made and list of files modified. Your session ends after this call.
